'''Interstate 75''' ('''I-75''') is a part of the [[Interstate Highway System]] that runs from [[Miami, Florida]], to [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]] in the [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan]]. I-75 enters [[Michigan]] from [[Ohio]] in the south, north of [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]] and runs generally northward through [[Detroit]], [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]] and [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]], crosses the [[Mackinac Bridge]], and ends at the [[Canada|Canadian]] border in Sault Ste. Marie. The freeway runs for approximately {{convert|396|mi|km}} on both of Michigan's peninsulas. The landscapes traversed by I-75 include [[Southern Michigan]] farmland, northern forests, suburban bedroom communities, and the urban core of Detroit. The freeway also uses three of the state's monumental bridges to cross major bodies of water. There are four [[List of auxiliary Interstate Highways|auxiliary Interstates]] in the state related to I-75, as well as nine current or former [[Business routes of Interstate 75 in Michigan|business routes]], with either Business Loop I-75 (BL I-75) or Business Spur I-75 (BS I-75) designations.

The freeway bears several names in addition to the I-75 designation. The southern segment was called the '''Detroit<U+2013>Toledo Expressway''' during planning in the 1950s and 1960s. Through Detroit, I-75 is the '''Fisher Freeway''' or the '''Walter P. Chrysler Freeway''', named for pioneers in the auto industry. Sections on either side of the Mackinac Bridge are the '''G. Mennen Williams Freeway''' or the '''Prentiss M. Brown Freeway''', named for politicians who helped get the bridge built. Officially, the entire length is the '''American Legion Memorial Highway''', after the [[American Legion|organization of the same name]]. Various sections carry components of the four [[Great Lakes Circle Tour]]s in the state.

Several [[Native Americans in the United States|Indian]] trails spanned the state along the general path of the modern freeway. After statehood, several of these were converted into [[plank road]]s that later became some of the first state highways. In the 1920s, five of these were added to the [[United States Numbered Highway System]]: [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US Highway&nbsp;2]] (US&nbsp;2), [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US&nbsp;10]], [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]], [[U.S. Route 25 in Michigan|US&nbsp;25]], and [[U.S. Route 27 in Michigan|US&nbsp;27]]. In the 1950s, a '''Michigan Turnpike''' was proposed as a [[toll road|tolled]], [[controlled-access highway]] in the Lower Peninsula. After passage of the [[Federal Highway Act of 1956]], this turnpike proposal was shelved as a free Interstate Highway was planned. Construction started in 1957, signs went up in 1959, and I-75 was completed in 1973. Since completion, the freeway has been upgraded with the construction of the [[Zilwaukee Bridge]] near Saginaw and improved connections to the [[Ambassador Bridge]] in Detroit.

==Route description==
Known as "Michigan's Main Street",<ref name=meyer>{{cite news |first= Zlati |last= Meyer |date= March 28, 2010 |title= You Haven't Lived Here Until You Drive I-75 Ohio to the Soo |url= http://www.freep.com/assets/freep/pdf/C4163055825.PDF |format= PDF |work= [[Detroit Free Press]] |page= 18A |issn= 1055-2758 |accessdate= October 30, 2012}}</ref> I-75 is listed on the [[National Highway System (United States)|National Highway System]] (NHS) for its entire length.<ref name=NHS-MI>{{cite map |title= National Highway System, Michigan |date= April&nbsp;23, 2006 |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |url= http://www.michigan.gov/documents/MDOT_NHS_Statewide_150626_7.pdf |format= PDF |accessdate= October&nbsp;7, 2008}}</ref> The NHS is a network of roadways important to the country's economy, defense, and mobility.<ref name=NHS>{{cite web |first1= Stefan |last1= Natzke |first2= Mike |last2= Neathery |first3= Kevin |last3= Adderly |lastauthoramp= yes |url= http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/planning/national_highway_system/ |title= What is the National Highway System? |work= National Highway System |publisher= [[Federal Highway Administration]] |date= June&nbsp;20, 2012 |accessdate= July&nbsp;1, 2012 }}</ref> The freeway is the busiest in the state: between [[M-8 (Michigan highway)|M-8]] (Davison Highway) and McNichols Road in Detroit approximately 194,300&nbsp;vehicles used the freeway on [[average annual daily traffic|average each day]] in 2010; in contrast the lowest traffic level was 3,208 vehicles between the [[M-48 (Michigan highway)|M-48]] and [[M-80 (Michigan highway)|M-80]] interchanges in [[Chippewa County, Michigan|Chippewa County]].<ref name=TMIS>{{cite web |author= Bureau of Transportation Planning |url= http://mdotnetpublic.state.mi.us/tmispublic/ |title= Traffic Monitoring Information System |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |year= 2012 |accessdate= October 30, 2012}}</ref> I-75 carries segments of all four [[Great Lakes Circle Tour]]s in the state. It is also the only highway located on both Michigan's [[Upper Peninsula of Michigan|Upper]] and [[Lower Peninsula of Michigan|Lower]] peninsulas (UP and LP, respectively).<ref name=MDOT12/> Between the Ohio state line and [[Kawkawlin, Michigan|Kawkawlin]], I-75 contains between a minimum of six and a maximum of ten lanes total; other sections vary between four and six lanes in total.<ref name=google/>

===Lake Erie shore and the Downriver communities===
[[File:I-75 exit 2 Michigan.jpg|thumb|left|I-75 approaching exit&nbsp;2 in Monroe County|alt=Photograph of]]
Crossing the state line north of [[Toledo, Ohio]], I-75 enters Michigan in [[Monroe County, Michigan|Monroe County]] carrying the [[Lake Erie Circle Tour]] (LECT) near the North Maumee Bay of [[Lake Erie]]. The freeway runs parallel to the shoreline of the Great Lake and past the community of [[Luna Pier, Michigan|Luna Pier]]. Further north, I-75 passes to the southeast of [[Monroe, Michigan|Monroe]] and crosses the [[River Raisin]] between the city and the river mouth. North of the river, the freeway turns further inland running through farmland. Near [[Newport, Michigan|Newport]], [[Interstate 275 (Michigan)|I-275]] splits off to the northwest and I-75 continues its northeasterly trek through Monroe County. When it crosses the [[Huron River (Michigan)|Huron River]], the trunkline enters [[Wayne County, Michigan|Wayne County]] between [[South Rockwood, Michigan|South Rockwood]] and [[Rockwood, Michigan|Rockwood]].<ref name=MDOT12>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |title= State Transportation Map |year= 2012 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:15&nbsp;mi&nbsp;/ 1&nbsp;cm:9&nbsp;km (main map); 1&nbsp;in:2.5&nbsp;mi&nbsp;/ 1&nbsp;cm:1.75&nbsp;km (inset) |at= Section B11<U+2013>G11, G11<U+2013>M14, M14<U+2013>N13, main map; section B8<U+2013>E11, E11<U+2013>H9, Detroit Area inset }}</ref><ref name=google>{{google maps |title= Overview Map of I-75 in Michigan |url= https://maps.google.com/maps?saddr=I-75+N&daddr=42.41798,-83.08751+to:Sault+Ste+Marie+International+Bridge&hl=en&sll=46.496915,-84.358006&sspn=0.056958,0.058279&geocode=FbTHfAIdLBAG-w%3BFTw_hwIdai8M-ylN2vRw_M0kiDFiEnNGSZxgpQ%3BFaypxQId-sH4-g&oq=Sault&mra=ls&via=1&t=h&z=7 |accessdate= October 27, 2012}}</ref>

On the north side of the county line, I-75 begins to run inland of, and parallel to, the [[Detroit River]], entering the [[Downriver]] area. The freeway turns northerly after the interchange with [[M-85 (Michigan highway)|M-85]] (Fort Street) near [[Gibraltar, Michigan|Gibraltar]], and the LECT departs I-75 to follow M-85 north of the interchange. The landscape transitions to suburban residential areas instead of farmland through this area. The freeway turns back northeasterly in [[Taylor, Michigan|Taylor]] and intersects the southern end of [[M-39 (Michigan highway)|M-39]] (Southfield Highway) in [[Lincoln Park, Michigan|Lincoln Park]]. I-75 crosses the [[Ecorse River]] and passes through an industrial area of Metro Detroit. Further north, the freeway spans the [[River Rouge (Michigan)|River Rouge]] in the southern part of Detroit.<ref name= MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

I-75 parallels to M-85 (Fort Street) and follows the Detroit River as far east as the [[Ambassador Bridge]]. Near the bridge's approaches, the freeway turns 90<U+00B0> away from the river and intersects the eastern end of [[Interstate 96|I-96]] before turning again to follow the river further inland. From there, I-75 meets [[M-10 (Michigan highway)|M-10]] (Lodge Freeway) and crosses under [[M-1 (Michigan highway)|M-1]] (Woodward Avenue). East of Woodward, the freeway travels past both [[Comerica Park]] and [[Ford Field]], homes of the [[Detroit Tigers]] and [[Detroit Lions]] professional sports teams, respectively.<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

===Detroit to the Tri-Cities===
[[File:I-75 Chrysler Freeway looking south.jpg|thumb|Looking south along the Chrysler Freeway to the Detroit skyline|alt=Photograph]]
Immediately east of Ford Field, I-75 turns northwesterly to follow the Chrysler Freeway away from the downtown Detroit area. The transition from the Fisher Freeway involves a set of one-lane ramps through the interchange with the connections to [[Interstate 375 (Michigan)|Interstate 375]] and [[M-3 (Michigan highway)|M-3]] (Gratiot Avenue). Heading north-northwesterly, I-75 passes to the east of the campus of [[Wayne State University]] and through an interchange with [[Interstate 94 in Michigan|I-94]] (Edsel Ford Freeway). The Chrysler Freeway passes to the west of [[Hamtramck, Michigan|Hamtramck]] and to the east of [[Highland Park, Michigan|Highland Park]], [[enclave]]s within Detroit. I-75 meets M-8 (Davison Freeway) and continues through residential areas of Detroit's northern side. North of [[M-102 (Michigan highway)|M-102]] (8&nbsp;Mile Road), the freeway crosses out of Detroit and into [[Oakland County, Michigan|Oakland County]]. The Chrysler Freeway jogs through the suburb of [[Hazel Park, Michigan|Hazel Park]],<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> site of the "worst freeway for accidents in Metro Detroit" at a curve near 9&nbsp;Mile Road.<ref name=oosting>{{cite news |first= Jonathan |last= Oosting |date= December 5, 2010 |title= Worst Freeway for Accidents in Metro Detroit? Stretch of I-75 Where Tanker Exploded Last Year |url= http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2010/12/worst_freeway_for_accidents_in.html |work= MLive |location= Detroit |publisher= [[Booth Newspapers]] |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref>

Further north, I-75 intersects [[Interstate 696|I-696]] near 10&nbsp;Mile Road. The freeway continues northward for about {{convert/spell|6|mi|km}} into [[Troy, Michigan|Troy]], where it turns westward. The route for I-75 zig-zags through Troy and [[Auburn Hills, Michigan|Auburn Hills]] as the freeway alternates from north<U+2013>south to east<U+2013>west to bypass [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]]. Near the [[M-59 (Michigan highway)|M-59]] interchange, I-75 passes the headquarters for [[Chrysler]]. Further north, by the [[M-24 (Michigan highway)|M-24]] interchange, it runs near [[The Palace of Auburn Hills]], home of the [[Detroit Pistons]]. The freeway traverses through additional suburban residential areas as it runs northwesterly away from Pontiac. These subdivisions end north of [[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]], which is the location of the northern terminus for [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]]. Continuing through [[Holly, Michigan|Holly]] and [[Newark, Oakland County, Michigan|Newark]], the freeway transitions back to a rural, wooded setting.<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

As I-75 approaches [[Grand Blanc, Michigan|Grand Blanc]], the landscape changes back to suburbs. [[Interstate 475 (Michigan)|I-475]] (UAW Freeway) splits off to the north to bypass the east side of [[Flint, Michigan|Flint]], and I-75 merges with [[U.S. Route 23 in Michigan|US&nbsp;23]]. The combined I-75/US&nbsp;23 turns northerly to round the west side of the city. I-75/US&nbsp;23 meets [[Interstate 69 in Michigan|I-69]] near the [[Bishop International Airport]] southwest of downtown Flint. The freeway continues northward along the western residential neighborhoods, encountering the northern end of I-475 near [[Mount Morris, Michigan|Mount Morris]]. I-75 passes to the west of [[Clio, Michigan|Clio]] and the east of [[Birch Run, Michigan|Birch Run]], the latter home to a large outlet mall. From there, the trunkline travels through farmland in southern [[Saginaw County, Michigan|Saginaw County]].<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

===Central Michigan===
[[File:I-75 MI exit 188.JPG|thumb|left|Split between I-75 and US&nbsp;23 west of Standish|alt=Photograph showing the]]
I-75/US&nbsp;23 enters the southern reaches of the suburban [[Tri-Cities (Michigan)|Tri-Cities]] at [[Bridgeport, Michigan|Bridgeport]] and proceeds northward through the area. The freeway passes to the east of downtown [[Saginaw, Michigan|Saginaw]]. [[Interstate 675 (Michigan)|I-675]] splits off to run westward into downtown, and I-75 curves around to the northwest to cross the [[Saginaw River]] on the [[Zilwaukee Bridge]] in the suburb of [[Zilwaukee, Michigan|Zilwaukee]]. North of the river, I-675 reconnects to I-75, which continues northward into [[Bay County, Michigan|Bay County]]. The freeway passes to the west of [[Bay City, Michigan|Bay City]], encountering the eastern end of the [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US&nbsp;10]] freeway. From there, I-75/US&nbsp;23 curves northwesterly to bypass Kawkawlin before continuing north to the [[Standish, Michigan|Standish]] area through farmlands inland from the [[Saginaw Bay]]. West of Standish, US&nbsp;23 splits to follow the [[Lake Huron]] shoreline, and I-75 turns northwesterly to run inland.<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

West of [[Sterling, Michigan|Sterling]], the landscape changes again; in this area the freeway enters forest lands. I-75 continues northwestward through [[Arenac County, Michigan|Arenac County]] and crosses into western [[Ogemaw County, Michigan|Ogemaw County]]. [[M-30 (Michigan highway)|M-30]] passes under the freeway without an interchange as I-75 rounds the west side of [[West Branch, Michigan|West Branch]]. On the northwest side of that city, [[M-55 (Michigan highway)|M-55]] merges onto I-75, and the two highways turn to run concurrently westward into [[Roscommon County, Michigan|Roscommon County]]. East of [[Prudenville, Michigan|Prudenville]], M-55 splits from the freeway. I-75 turns northward to curve around the east of [[Houghton Lake (Michigan)|Houghton]] and [[Higgins Lake|Higgins]] lakes. Turning back to the northwest, the trunkline bypasses [[Roscommon, Michigan|Roscommon]] to the south and transfers into southern [[Crawford County, Michigan|Crawford County]]. About {{convert/spell|5|mi|km}} north of the county line, I-75 meets the northern end of [[U.S. Route 127 in Michigan|US&nbsp;127]],<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> the former [[U.S. Route 27 in Michigan|US&nbsp;27]].<ref name=ranzenberger>{{cite news |url= http://docs.newsbank.com/openurl?ctx_ver=z39.88-2004&rft_id=info:sid/iw.newsbank.com:AWNB:MPMB&rft_val_format=info:ofi/fmt:kev:mtx:ctx&rft_dat=12050B7ED0067678&svc_dat=InfoWeb:aggregated5&req_dat=0B0A2F7372D54C748F8A8C4C17175B68 |title= US&nbsp;127 Signs Getting Updated |first= Mark |last= Ranzenberger |work= [[Morning Sun (Mount Pleasant)|The Morning Sun]] |location= Mount Pleasant, MI |accessdate= August 23, 2012 |date= April 27, 2008 |pages= 1A, 6A |oclc= 22378715}}</ref>

===Northern Michigan===
[[File:I-75 MI exit 254.jpg|thumb|Exit&nbsp;254 south of Grayling|alt=Photograph of]]
After the US&nbsp;127 interchange, I-75 turns northward, and passes to the east of [[Grayling, Michigan|Grayling]]. There are a pair of interchanges on either end of town for [[Interstate 75 Business (Grayling, Michigan)|BL I-75]], and the southern one is a [[partial interchange]]; only northbound I-75 traffic may access the business loop and traffic entering the freeway may only access southbound I-75. There is no interchange further north for [[M-72 (Michigan highway)|M-72]]; access to that highway is provided through the business loop. On the north side of Grayling, there is a full interchange for BL I-75/[[M-93 (Michigan highway)|M-93]] that provides the southbound I-75 connection to M-72 as well as access from both directions to the [[Hartwick Pines State Park]].<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

Crossing into southern [[Otsego County, Michigan|Otsego County]], I-75 continues northward through [[Northern Michigan]] forests. It passes to the east of the community of [[Waters, Michigan|Waters]] and [[Otsego Lake (Michigan)|Otsego Lake]]. North of exit&nbsp;279, I-75 proceeds by the [[Gaylord Regional Airport]] and crosses the [[45th parallel north|45th Parallel]], the halfway mark between the [[Equator]] and the [[North Pole]] by latitude. The freeway then traverses the west side of [[Gaylord, Michigan|Gaylord]] and continues through forests in the northern sections of the county. North of [[Vanderbilt, Michigan|Vanderbilt]], I-75 enters southern [[Cheboygan County, Michigan|Cheboygan County]],<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> assuming the G. Mennen Williams Freeway name.<ref name=barnett88/>

I-75 continues northward through Cheboygan County, passing the community of [[Indian River, Michigan|Indian River]] and spanning the [[Indian River (Mullett Lake)|river of the same name]]. North of town, the freeway traverses the area between [[Burt Lake|Burt]] and [[Mullett Lake|Mullett]] lakes before intersecting the southern end of [[M-27 (Michigan highway)|M-27]]; that highway provides access to [[Topinabee, Michigan|Topinabee]] and [[Cheboygan, Michigan|Cheboygan]]. I-75 continues northward through tree farms and other agricultural properties in rural Cheboygan County. Cheboygan is accessible by way of interchanges for [[C-64 (Michigan county highway)|C-64]] and [[C-66 (Michigan county highway)|C-66]], a pair of [[List of County-Designated Highways in Michigan|county-designated highways]] in this area. North of C-66, I-75 turns northwesterly. The freeway meets the northern end of [[U.S. Route 31 in Michigan|US&nbsp;31]] and picks up the [[Lake Michigan Circle Tour]] (LMCT) designation before entering [[Emmet County, Michigan|Emmet County]] on the south side of [[Mackinaw City, Michigan|Mackinaw City]]. I-75 then parallels the county line on the west side of the village, meeting the northern end of US&nbsp;23. After that interchange, the [[Lake Huron Circle Tour]] (LHCT) merges in from the south. There is one more interchange along the freeway before I-75 ascends the approaches to the [[Mackinac Bridge]].<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/>

===Mackinac Bridge===
The Mackinac Bridge carries I-75 across the [[Straits of Mackinac]] that separate Michigan's Upper and Lower peninsulas; the straits also form the connection between Lakes [[Lake Michigan|Michigan]] and Huron.<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> The structure, unlike the rest of the state highways in Michigan like I-75, is under the maintenance and control of the [[Mackinac Bridge Authority]] (MBA).{{#tag:ref|The MBA is an independent state agency responsible for the Mackinac Bridge and thus maintains that section of the overall highway system. The MBA works with MDOT but does not report to it. The executive secretary of the MBA is appointed by MDOT with MBA approval.<ref name=MBAPR>{{cite news |title= Bridge Legislation Signed |work=[[The Grand Rapids Press]] |date= December 29, 2005 |agency= Associated Press |page=B3 |oclc= 9975013}}</ref>|name=MBA|group=lower-alpha}} The authority collects a toll from traffic that crosses the bridge,<ref name=gould/> which {{as of|2012|01|01|df=US|lc=y}}, is $4 for passenger cars and $5 per axle for commercial vehicles and motorhomes.<ref>{{cite news |title= Mackinac Bridge Toll Increase |date= December 30, 2011 |url= http://www.uppermichiganssource.com/news/story.aspx?id=702515 |location= Negaunee, MI |publisher= [[WLUC-TV]] |agency= Associated Press |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}</ref> In addition to cash, the MBA offers a pre-paid debit card option for the payment of tolls.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tom |last= Greenwood |date= April 18, 2009 |title= 'Quick Card' payment to be used at Mackinac Bridge |work= [[The Detroit News]] |url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DTNB&s_site=detnews&f_site=detnews&f_sitename=Detroit+News%2C+The+%28MI%29&p_multi=DTNB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=127A91099BD59C40&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D |page= 3A |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}{{subscription required}}</ref> The authority also provides a driver assistance program that will drive vehicles across the bridge at no additional charge; motorists who use the service have a [[Gephyrophobia|fear of bridges]].<ref>{{cite news |first= Kim |last= Schneider |date= May 20, 2007 |title= Fear the Mighty Mac? They get you over it |url= http://blog.mlive.com/michigan_travel/2007/05/fear_the_mighty_mac_they_get_y.html |work= MLive |publisher= Booth Newspapers |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}</ref> Because the bridge normally only allows motor vehicles, bicyclists and snowmobiles shuttled across are subject to fees. The authority maintains a small police department to patrol the bridge and escort vehicles across,<ref name=gould>{{cite news |first= Karen |last= Gould |date= July 26, 2007 |url= http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-07-26/bridge/122.html |title= A Day in the Life of the Mackinac Bridge |work= [[The St. Ignace News]] |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Tom |last= Carr |date= July 1, 2007 |title= Troubled Over Bridged Waters: Mackinac Crew Offers Rides to Those with Severe Phobia |url= http://static.record-eagle.com/2007/jul/01mack-feature.htm |work= [[Traverse City Record-Eagle]]|pages= 1E, 2E |oclc= 30098364 |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}</ref> and a pair of radio station transmitters that broadcast bridge conditions and travel information on AM&nbsp;530 and AM&nbsp;1610.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.michiguide.com/dials/amtis/wnhc787.html |title= WNHC787 AM 530 St. Ignace / AM 1610 Mackinaw City |work= MichiGuide |accessdate= April 5, 2013}}</ref>

===Upper Peninsula===
[[File:I-75 north of St. Ignace Michigan.jpg|thumb|left|North of St. Ignace|alt=Photograph of I-75]]
North of the Mackinac Bridge, I-75 passes to the west of downtown [[St. Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]], traveling between the [[Father Marquette National Memorial]] and the [[Straits State Park]]. There is an interchange north of the toll plaza that marks the eastern end of [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]] in the state. The LMCT departs I-75 to follow US&nbsp;2 while the LHCT follows [[Interstate 75 Business (St. Ignace, Michigan)|BL I-75]] through town. The freeway curves around the [[Mackinac County Airport]] and meets the northern end of the business loop near [[Castle Rock (Michigan)|Castle Rock]]; the LHCT returns to I-75 at that interchange as well. Continuing northward, [[M-123 (Michigan highway)|M-123]] (Tahquamenon Trail) intersects from the west as the freeway parallels [[H-63 (Michigan county highway)|H-63]] (Mackinac Trail),<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> the former route of US&nbsp;2.<ref>{{cite news |first= Edward |last= Collier |date= July 29, 1960 |title= Michigan's Upper Peninsula: Hiawatha's Scenic Land Opened Up by Might Bridge |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/titusville-herald/1960-07-29/page-8?tag=us+2+mackinac+trail&rtserp=tags/us-2-mackinac-trail?ndt=by&py=1960&pey=1969 |work= The Titusville Herald |page= 8 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> I-75 crosses the [[Carp River (Mackinac County)|Carp River]] and follows the shores of [[St. Martin Bay]] before meeting [[M-134 (Michigan highway)|M-134]]. At that interchange, the LHCT departs again to run eastward. Through this area, the freeway continues northeasterly, traversing the Eastern Unit of the [[Hiawatha National Forest]].<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/><ref name=RM13>{{cite map |publisher= [[Rand McNally]] |year= 2013 |title= The Road Atlas |edition= 2013 Walmart |page= 50 |section= E8<U+2013>F8 |isbn= 0-528-00626-6}}</ref>

I-75 crosses the [[Pine River (Mackinac County, Michigan)|Pine River]] before entering Chippewa County. The freeway takes a more northerly track as it travels under M-48 without an interchange. Further north, M-48 curves around to connect I-75 with [[Rudyard, Michigan|Rudyard]], and the freeway turns back to continue northeastward. About {{convert/spell|5|mi|km}} northeast of Rudyard, I-75 passes next to [[Chippewa County International Airport]], the former [[Kincheloe Air Force Base]] in [[Kinross, Michigan|Kinross]] and [[Kincheloe, Michigan|Kincheloe]]. North of there in [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]], the freeway intersects [[M-28 (Michigan highway)|M-28]] (9&nbsp;Mile Road). Beyond that interchange, I-75 picks up the [[Lake Superior Circle Tour]] (LSCT) designation, which it carries the rest of the way north. On the south side of [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Sault Ste. Marie]], the freeway meets [[Interstate 75 Business (Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan)|BS I-75]] and picks up the LHCT designation one more time. I-75 rounds the west side of the city, passes the [[Sault Ste. Marie Municipal Airport]] and the campus of [[Lake Superior State University]] before meeting the [[U.S. Customs and Border Protection|customs]] and toll plazas for the [[Sault Ste. Marie International Bridge|International Bridge]].<ref name=MDOT12/><ref name=google/> From there, I-75 crosses the two-lane bridge and terminates at the [[Canada<U+2013>United States border|Canadian border]].<ref name="end" group=lower-alpha/> {{As of|2012|04|01|df=y}}, the toll rates on the bridge are $3 for passenger vehicles, $2.10 for commuters, and $4 per axle for commercial vehicles; currently the same toll rate is assessed in [[US dollar]]s and [[Canadian dollar]]s.<ref name= IBAtoll >{{cite news |title= Tolls Rise for Some at Sault International Bridge |agency= Associated Press |date= March 25, 2012 }}</ref> Motorists have the option to pay with cash or an IQ Card, an [[electronic toll collection]] debit card that uses [[radio-frequency identification]] technology.<ref>{{cite news |first= David |last= Helwig |date= |title= New Bridge Cards Available Tomorrow |url= http://www.sootoday.com/content/news/full_story.asp?StoryNumber=26102 |publisher= SooToday.com |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref>

==History==

===Indian trails to state highways===
[[File:Michigan's Indian trails.png|thumb|upright|Map of the pre-statehood Indian trails|alt=Black and white map]]
Before Michigan became a state, the first land transportation corridors were the [[Native Americans in the United States|Indian]] trails.<ref name=morrison1>[[#Morrison|Morrison]], p.&nbsp;1.</ref> The [[French-Indian Trail]] ran through southeastern Michigan between [[Toledo, Ohio|Toledo]], Monroe and Detroit. The [[Saginaw Trail]] ran north from Detroit to the Saginaw area where it connected with the original [[Mackinaw Trail]] that ran roughly parallel to, and west of, the modern I-75. Another path, the Cheboygan Trail, ran parallel to the modern freeway to the east between the West Branch area and Cheboygan. In the UP, an extension of the Mackinac Trail connected St. Ignace and Sault Ste. Marie.<ref name=mason18>[[#Mason|Mason]], p.&nbsp;18.</ref> In the 19th century, the [[Michigan Legislature]] chartered private companies to build and operate [[plank road]]s or turnpikes in the state, many of which replaced the original Indian trails. These roads were originally made of oak planks, but later legislation permitted gravel as well.<ref name=morrison7-8>[[#Morrison|Morrison]], pp.&nbsp;7<U+2013>8.</ref> By the first decade of the 20th century, only 23 of the 202&nbsp;chartered turnpikes were still in operation; many companies that received a charter never built their specified roadways. The remaining plank roads were turned over to the state or purchased by railway companies in the early part of the century.<ref name= mason4>[[#Mason|Mason]], p.&nbsp;4.</ref>

The [[Michigan State Trunkline Highway System|State Trunkline Highway System]] was formed on May 13, 1913, and several sections of the system were designated along the course of the then-future I-75. Division&nbsp;1 connected the Ohio state line northeasterly to Detroit, and Division&nbsp;2 connected Detroit with Mackinaw City. A branch of Division&nbsp;7 ran north from St. Ignace to Sault Ste. Marie.<ref name=STLHA>[[#MichLeg|Michigan Legislature]], p.&nbsp;1868</ref> The system was signposted in 1919,<ref name=press-1919-09-20>{{cite news |title=Michigan May Do Well Following Wisconsin's Road Marking System |work= The Grand Rapids Press |date= September&nbsp;20, 1919 |page= 10 |oclc= 9975013}}</ref> and those highways were marked on maps for the first time. The first [[M-10 (Michigan highway)|M-10]] was designated along the highways from Ohio through Detroit to Standish.<ref group=lower-alpha>Northeast of Standish, M-10 ran along the Lake Huron shoreline.</ref> [[M-76 (Michigan highway)|M-76]] connected Standish with Grayling, where the first [[M-14 (Michigan highway)|M-14]] ran northward to Cheboygan. From there, M-10 connected to Mackinaw City.<ref name=MSHD19LP>{{cite map |publisher= [[Michigan State Highway Department]] |title= State of Michigan: Lower Peninsula |date= July&nbsp;1, 1919 |cartography= MSHD }}</ref> In the UP, [[M-12 (Michigan highway)|M-12]] connected St. Ignace with Sault Ste. Marie along a route to the east of the old Mackinac Trail.<ref name=MSHD19UP>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= State of Michigan: Upper Peninsula |date= July 1, 1919 |cartography= MSHD }}</ref> When the [[United States Numbered Highway System]] was formed on November 11, 1926, most of these highways were redesignated as part of the national system. From the state line northward, M-10 was included as a part of [[U.S. Route 24 in Michigan|US&nbsp;24]] and [[U.S. Route 25 in Michigan|US&nbsp;25]]. At Detroit, M-10 was used as a part of [[U.S. Route 10 in Michigan|US&nbsp;10]]. North of Grayling, M-14 was redesignated as a part of [[U.S. Route 27 in Michigan|US&nbsp;27]]. M-12 was used for [[U.S. Route 2 in Michigan|US&nbsp;2]].<ref name=USH>{{cite map |publisher= [[Bureau of Public Roads]] |title= United States System of Highways |cartography= [[American Association of State Highway Officials]] |url= http://www.okladot.state.ok.us/hqdiv/p-r-div/maps/misc-maps/1926us.pdf |date= November&nbsp;11, 1926 |accessdate= May 10, 2008 |format= PDF |oclc= 32889555}}</ref>

The [[Michigan State Highway Department]] (MSHD){{#tag:ref|The Michigan State Highway Department was reorganized into the Michigan Department of State Highways and Transportation on August&nbsp;23, 1973.<ref name="MMM27">[[#Kulsea|Kulsea]], p.&nbsp;27.</ref> The name was shortened to its current form in 1978.<ref name="MMM30-1">[[#Kulsea|Kulsea]], pp.&nbsp;30<U+2013>1.</ref>|name=MDOT|group=lower-alpha}} rerouted US&nbsp;2 in 1933 between [[Rogers Park, Michigan|Rogers Park]] and Sault Ste. Marie. The new routing followed Mackinac Trail instead of turning east to [[Cedarville, Michigan|Cedarville]] and north to Sault Ste. Marie; the former routing was given the [[M-121 (Michigan highway)|M<U+2011>121]] designation.<ref name=MSHD33-05>{{cite map |publisher=Michigan State Highway Department |title=Official Michigan Highway Map |date=May&nbsp;1, 1933 |cartography= Rand McNally |section=}}</ref><ref name=MSHD33-09>{{cite map |publisher=Michigan State Highway Department |title=Official Michigan Highway Map |date=September&nbsp;1, 1933 |cartography= Rand McNally |section=}}</ref>

===Turnpikes and freeways===
By 1945, a [[divided highway]] designated Alternate US&nbsp;24 (ALT US&nbsp;24) was opened from the state line north to [[Erie, Michigan|Erie]].<ref name=MSHD45-10>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map of Michigan |date= October&nbsp;1, 1945 |section= N13 }}</ref> After World War II, the MSHD planned to convert several highways in the state to freeways. In planning maps from 1947, the modern I-75 corridor was included in the system that later became the [[Interstate Highway System]].<ref name="NSHIS47">{{cite map |url= http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Interstate_Highway_plan_August_2,_1947_big_text.jpg |title= National System of Interstate Highways |publisher= [[Public Roads Administration]] |date=August&nbsp;2, 1947 |accessdate= September&nbsp;4, 2010}}</ref> It was also included in the ''General Location of National System of Interstate Highways Including All Additional Routes at Urban Areas Designated in September 1955'', or ''Yellow Book'' after the cover color, that was released in 1955 as the federal government readied plans for the freeway system.<ref name="YBD">{{cite map |url= http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Interstate_Highway_plan_September_1955.jpg |title= General Location of National System of Interstate Highways Including All Additional Routes at Urban Areas Designated in September 1955 (Yellow Book)  |publisher= Bureau of Public Roads |month=September |year= 1955 |accessdate= September&nbsp;4, 2010 |oclc= 4165975}}</ref>

[[File:Michigan Turnpike map 1955.png|thumb|left|upright|1955 map of the proposed Michigan Turnpike|alt=Black and white map]]
The Michigan Turnpike Authority (MTA), an agency which was created in 1951,<ref>{{cite report |author= Staff |title= Section 394 Report: Analysis of Transportation Funding Distribution Formula |url= http://www.micountyroads.org/PDF/Sec_394_Report_2010.pdf |format= PDF |date= March 1, 2010 |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |page= 12 |accessdate= October 28, 2012}}</ref> proposed the construction of a [[toll highway|toll freeway]] to run north<U+2013>south in the state. The original termini for the turnpike were Bridgeport and Rockwood.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8YQ_AAAAIBAJ&sjid=TVUMAAAAIBAJ&pg=4841,1977765&dq=ohio-turnpike+opening&hl=en |title= Michigan To Push Its North<U+2013>South Turnpike: Toll Road To Link Centers of Industrial Areas |work= [[Youngstown Vindicator]] |date= February 21, 1955 |page= 2 |accessdate= October 30, 2012 |oclc= 5424159}}</ref> The state highway commissioner at the time, [[Charles Ziegler]], distrusted a separate agency dealing with statewide road building at the time, and he worked to stall progress on any proposed turnpikes.<ref>{{cite news |last= Bagley |first= Les |title= Autos Across Mackinac: Michigan Decides Against Building Turnpikes |url= http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2007-10-25/columns/039.html |work= The St. Ignace News |page= |date= October 25, 2007 |accessdate= October 30, 2012 |oclc= 36250796}}</ref> Ziegler, who had a seat on the MTA board, publicly sparred with authority chairman George Higgins, even announcing that the MSHD would build a parallel freeway that would "reduce tolls on the turnpike 40 to 50 percent" according to consultants.<ref>{{cite news |title= Ziegler Pushes Plans For Free Road Despite Proposed Turnpike |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/marshall-evening-chronicle/1955-08-09?tag=michigan+turnpike+bond&rtserp=tags/michigan-turnpike-bond |work= [[Marshall Evening Chronicle]] |agency= [[United Press International]] |page= 1 |date= August 9, 1955 |oclc= 18110507 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> Trucking interests in the state also opposed the projects, preferring a moderate gas tax increase over any tolls.<ref name=HP55>{{cite news |title= Highway Politics |url=  http://newspaperarchive.com/saint-joseph-herald-press/1955-09-23/page-8?tag=michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/michigan-turnpike |work= The Herald-Press |location= St. Joseph, MI |date= September 23, 1955 |page= 8 |oclc= 10117184 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> Detroit denied the MTA permission to route a turnpike through the city over issues related to the River Rouge, Rouge Park and access across the [[right-of-way (transportation)|right-of-way]].<ref name=CSPike/> After a lawsuit by City of Dearborn, the legislation creating the authority was upheld by the [[Michigan Supreme Court]] in 1955, and the authority was allowed to sell bonds for its Bridgeport<U+2013>Rockwood<!--article says Saginaw<U+2013>Flat Rock--><ref>{{cite news |title= Michigan Turnpike Law Upheld |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1368&dat=19551202&id=m2ZQAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vQ8EAAAAIBAJ&pg=5226,909060 |work= [[The Milwaukee Sentinel]] |agency= Associated Press |date= December 2, 1955 |page= B2 |accessdate= October 30, 2012 |issn= 1052-4479}}</ref> and Detroit<U+2013>Chicago toll roads.<ref>{{cite news |title= Expressway Hopes Soar |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1955-12-05/page-2?tag=michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/michigan-turnpike |work= [[The Herald-Palladium|The News-Palladium]] |location= Benton Harbor, MI |page= 2 |date= December 5, 1955 |accessdate= July 19, 2013 |oclc= 10117334}}</ref>

The original planning maps plotted the first turnpike to the west of Detroit, running near US&nbsp;24 (Telegraph Road).<ref>{{cite report |author= Coverdale and Colpitts |title= Report on Estimated Traffic and Earnings of the Proposed Michigan Turnpike, Project No&nbsp;1, North-South Turnpike |url= http://babel.hathitrust.org/cgi/pt?id=mdp.39015024498522;seq=26;view=1up;num=2 |location= New York |publisher= Michigan Turnpike Authority |year= 1955 |page= 2 |oclc= 35260166 |accessdate= October 30, 2012 }}</ref> This route was later proposed for I-75 itself; I-275 would have been the freeway to loop into downtown Detroit.<ref name =richard1986-04-03>{{cite news |last=Richard |first=Tim |title= I-275: The Interstate that Isn't |work= [[Livonia Observer]] |date= April 3, 1986 |oclc= 22646576}}</ref>  The proposed length was increased by December 1955; the extended Michigan Turnpike would have run from a connection across the Ohio state line to Toledo north through Detroit and Saginaw and eventually to the southern end of the Mackinac Bridge.<ref name=CSPike>{{cite news |title= Cross-State 'Pike Planned |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1955-12-14/page-16?tag=michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/michigan-turnpike?page=2 |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency= United Press International |date= December&nbsp;14, 1955 |page= 16 |accessdate= October&nbsp;31, 2012 |oclc= 30098364}}</ref> By the following April, any extensions were cancelled leaving the turnpike to its original termini; the east<U+2013>west companion road was also cancelled at that time.<ref>{{cite news |title= Michigan Drops Detroit<U+2013>Chicago Turnpike Plans: Mackinac Extension of Saginaw Toll Road Also Abandoned |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fscwAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ugAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7055,1622280&dq=michigan+turnpike&hl=en |work= [[Toledo Blade]] |agency= Associated Press |date= April 18, 1956 |page= 5 |oclc= 12962635 |accessdate= October&nbsp;31, 2012}}</ref> The MTA proposed a state constitutional amendment in January 1956 that would allow the Michigan Legislature to issue state-guaranteed bonds for part of the MTA's construction expenses.<ref>{{cite news |title= Pike Bond Issue Asked in Michigan: $300&nbsp;Million Sought for Toll Highways |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=w1dIAAAAIBAJ&sjid=uQAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2063,1647331&dq=michigan+turnpike+bond&hl=en |work= Toledo Blade |agency= Associated Press |oclc= 12962635 |date= January 26, 1956 |page= 8 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> According to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', the authority "struggled for survival" in the face of opposition from the MSHD just two months later; the department's actions impaired the authority's appropriations from the state legislature and its ability to sell the necessary bonds to pay for construction.<ref>{{cite news |title= Michigan Pike Agency's Shaky Status Dims Chance for Early Issue |author= Staff Reporter |work= [[The Wall Street Journal]] |date=March 27, 1956 |page= 20 |issn= 0099-9660 |url= http://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/djreprints/access/397598621.html?dids=397598621:397598621&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:AI&type=historic&date=Mar+27%2C+1956&author=&pub=Wall+Street+Journal&desc=Michigan+Pike+Agency's+Shaky+Status+Dims+Chance+for+Early+Issue |accessdate= July 19, 2013}} {{subscription required}}</ref> When the federal government approved the [[Federal Aid Highway Act of 1956]], Ziegler and the MSHD announced plans for a full freeway to run north through the Lower Peninsula and continue across to the Upper Peninsula. This announcement undermined the efforts to build the Michigan Turnpike.<ref>{{cite news |last= Bagley |first= Les |date=  January 17, 2008 |title= Autos Across Mackinac: Bridge Construction Continues; Tourism Down |url= http://www.stignacenews.com/news/2008-01-17/columns/053.html |work= The St. Ignace News |accessdate= October 30, 2012 |oclc= 36250796}}</ref> By August 1956, the MTA voted to reduce its operations to a skeleton staff,<ref>{{cite news |title= See Scant Chance for Highway |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=01JOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=dzwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4676,5262323&dq=michigan-turnpike&hl=en |work= [[Ludington Daily News]] |agency= Associated Press |date= August 21, 1956 |page= 1 |oclc= 27033604 |accessdate= October&nbsp;31, 2012}}</ref> but moved forward in May 1957 on a bond sale to finance construction of the roadway.<ref>{{cite news |title= World News Summary |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dTAxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=njwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5253,1281335&dq=michigan-turnpike&hl=en
|work= Ludington Daily News |date= May 25, 1957 |agency= Associated Press |page= 1 |accessdate= October&nbsp;31, 2012 |oclc= 27033604 }}</ref> Financiers stated such a sale was only feasible if the turnpike was to be safe from competition.<ref>{{cite news |title= Turnpike Authority Studies Financing |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1957-06-21/page-17?tag=bond+michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/bond?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1950&pey=1959&pep=michigan-turnpike&psb=date  |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency= United Press International |page= 17 |date= June 21, 1957 |oclc= 30098364 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> The Michigan Townships Association called for the abolition of the MTA in 1958.<ref>{{cite news |title= Changes Are Opposed by Townships: Constitutional Convention Hit |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1958-01-17/page-10?tag=bond+michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/bond?ndt=by&pci=7&pep=michigan-turnpike&pey=1959&psb=date&psi=52&py=1950 |work= The News-Palladium |location= Benton Harbor, MI |agency= Associated Press |oclc= 10117334 |page= 10 |date= January 17, 1958 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> The legislature killed a bill to do so in June 1959,<ref>{{cite news |title= Legislature Scraps 450&nbsp;State Bills: Agenda Cleared of Non-Essentials |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1959-06-06/page-10?tag=bond+michigan+turnpike&rtserp=tags/bond?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1950&pey=1959&pep=michigan-turnpike&psb=date |work= The News-Palladium |location= Benton Harbor, MI |agency= Associated Press |page= 10 |date= June 6, 1959 |oclc= 10117334 |accessdate= July 19, 2013}}</ref> but it later voted to repeal the act that created the authority in 1962.<ref>{{cite news |title= Legislature Moves To Kill 15&nbsp;Obsolete Laws |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=7HowAAAAIBAJ&sjid=76oFAAAAIBAJ&pg=2130,4726505&dq=michigan-turnpike&hl=en  |work= [[Argus-Press|The Owosso Argus-Press]] |agency= Associated Press |date= February 28, 1962<U+00A0>|page= 16 |oclc= 9802802 |accessdate= October&nbsp;31, 2012}}</ref>

===Interstate Highway era===
The first sections of freeway for I-75 were opened in 1957, beginning with the southern section near the Ohio state line opened in October 1957.<ref>{{cite news |title= Ohio, Michigan Dedicate New Expressway |work= [[Chicago Tribune|Chicago Daily Tribune]] |date= May&nbsp;23, 1959 |page=3 |oclc= 1554151}}<!--"Michigan completed its end of the expressway in October 1957, ahead of Ohio."--></ref> The [[Mackinac Bridge]] was opened to traffic on November&nbsp;1, 1957; a new section of freeway and an [[interchange (road)|interchange]] connected US&nbsp;2 to the bridge.<ref name=kulsea27>[[#Kulsea|Kulsea]], p.&nbsp;22.</ref> The MSHD formally proposed the I-75 number in 1958.<ref name=RINRM58>{{cite web |url= http://nwindianahwys.homestead.com/michiplan.html |archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20040805182658/nwindianahwys.homestead.com/michiplan.html |archivedate= August&nbsp;5, 2004 |accessdate= September&nbsp;4, 2010 |title= Recommended Interstate Route Numbering for Michigan |date= April&nbsp;25, 1958 |author= Staff |publisher=Michigan State Highway Department}}</ref> On June&nbsp;30 of that year, the first stretch of the "Fenton<U+2013>Clio Expressway" opened.<ref name=argus1958>{{cite news |title=Fenton<U+2013>Clio X-Way Big Time Saver |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=_lIvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=JasFAAAAIBAJ&pg=5987,7380675&dq=fenton-clio+expressway&hl=en |work= The Owosso Argus-Press |date=June 28, 1958 |page=9 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=April 20, 2011 |oclc= 9802802}}</ref> Construction on the Chrysler Freeway in Detroit started on January 30, 1959.<ref name=barnett233/> The I-75 signs were first installed along the Detroit<U+2013>Toledo Expressway in October 1959, replacing US&nbsp;24A signage in the Monroe area,<ref name=HP1959-10-13>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/saint-joseph-herald-press/1959-10-13/page-3?tag=michigan+interstate+75&rtserp=tags/michigan?pep=interstate-75&pr=30&psb=dateasc&page=2&pd=1&ndt=bd&pe=22&pem=3&py=1956&pm=1&pey=2013 |title= Interstate&nbsp;75 Road Markers Are Unveiled |work= [[The Herald-Palladium|The Herald-Press]] |location= St. Joseph, MI |agency= [[Associated Press]] |date= October 13, 1959 |page= 3 |accessdate= March 22, 2013 |oclc= 10117184}}</ref> after the state waited for final approval of the numbering system to be used in the state.<ref name=blade1959-06-04>{{cite news |title= Michigan Delays Road Number System |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=mb1OAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9AAEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7401,5582043&dq=interstate+opening+michigan&hl=en |work= Toledo Blade |agency= Associated Press |date= June&nbsp;4, 1959 |page= 11 |oclc= 12962635 |accessdate= November&nbsp;21, 2010}}</ref>

[[File:I-75 (MI 1957).svg|thumb|right|80px|Shields such as this one bearing the state name were originally used when I-75 was first signed|alt=I-75 marker with Michigan above the number]]
In November 1960, sections of freeway opened from Indian River north to the southern Mackinac Bridge approaches in Mackinaw City and from St. Ignace to [[Evergreen Shores, Michigan|Evergreen Shores]],<ref name=blade1960>{{cite news |title= Michigan To Open 35 More Miles of Freeway |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=2rlOAAAAIBAJ&sjid=CAEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2713,1527983&dq=michigan+open+%7C+construction+interstate-75&hl=en |work= [[Toledo Blade|The Blade]] |location= Toledo, OH |agency= Associated Press |date= November 8, 1960 |page= 19 |oclc= 12962717 |accessdate= March 22, 2013}}</ref> and by December, the section of freeway running between Evergreen Shores and [[M-123 (Michigan highway)|M<U+2011>123]] was scheduled to open.<ref name=HP1960-10-17>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/daily-globe/1961-12-22/page-3?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1960&pey=1961&pep=interstate-75 |title= 122&nbsp;Miles of Freeway To Be Opened by Dec. 15 |work= The Herald-Press |location= St. Joseph, MI |page= 3 |date= October 17, 1960 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 10117184}}</ref> The next year the original [[Zilwaukee Bridge]], a [[bascule bridge]] across the [[Saginaw River]] was opened<ref name=zilwaukee1961>{{cite news |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=lcQsAAAAIBAJ&sjid=OxMEAAAAIBAJ&pg=4037,2884367&dq=michigan+open+%7C+construction+interstate-75&hl=en |title= Michigan Town Wants Used Bridge |work= [[Wilmington Morning Star]] |date= December 11, 1979 |page= 3D |agency= Associated Press |accessdate= March 22, 2013 |issn= 0163-402X}}</ref> along with a section of freeway north to Kawkawlin.<ref name=MSHD60>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1960 |section= C10<U+2013>E10, J12<U+2013>L12 }} (Includes all changes through July&nbsp;1, 1960)</ref><ref name=MSHD61>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1961 |section= C10<U+2013>G10, J12<U+2013>K12 }} (Includes all changes through July&nbsp;1, 1961)</ref> That September, the section between Gaylord and [[Vanderbilt, Michigan|Vanderbilt]] was completed,<ref name= HP1961-09-01>{{cite news |title= Bypasses Gaylord |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/saint-joseph-herald-press/1962-09-01/page-4?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?pep=interstate-75&page=5&psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1962&pey=1963 |work= The Herald-Press |location= St. Joseph, MI |agency= Associated Press |date= September 1, 1962 |page= 2 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 10117184}}</ref> and in October 1961, the first segment of I-75 near [[Grayling, Michigan|Grayling]] opened, connecting [[M-18 (Michigan highway)|M-18]] with the city.<ref name=LDN1961-10-09>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/ludington-daily-news/1961-10-09/page-8?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1960&pey=1961&pep=interstate-75 |title= 75 Opened |work= Ludington Daily News |agency= Associated Press |date= October 9, 1961 |page= 8 |oclc= 27033604 |accessdate= March 23, 2013}}</ref> By the end of the year, the freeway was completed between [[Kinross, Michigan|Kinross]] and [[Dafter, Michigan|Dafter]] in the UP,<ref name=IDG1961-12-22>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/daily-globe/1961-12-22/page-3?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1960&pey=1961&pep=interstate-75 |title= Upper Peninsula To Get Many Highway Projects Next Year |work= [[Ironwood Daily Globe]] |page= 8 |date= December 22, 1961 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 10890811}}</ref> and the former segment of US&nbsp;27 between Grayling and Gaylord was turned back to local control. After this individual segment of freeway was completed, it left a gap between Gaylord and Indian River that was designated "TO I-75" on maps for the former segment of US&nbsp;27, and US&nbsp;27 was truncated to about {{convert/spell|5|mi|km}} south of Grayling.<ref name=MSHD61/><ref name=MSHD62>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1962 |section= C11, F10<U+2013>G10, G10<U+2013>J12, K12<U+2013>L13}}</ref> The {{convert|12|mi|km|0|adj=on}} section of I-75 was opened between Gaylord and Waters in July 1962.<ref name=argus62>{{cite news |title=State Briefs |work= The Owosso Argus-Press  |date=July 7, 1962 |page=4 |oclc= 9802802}}</ref> Another temporary "TO I-75" designation was applied along US&nbsp;10 and US&nbsp;27 from Bay City to Grayling.<ref name=MSHD62/>

On October 25, 1962, the section of freeway from [[M-24 (Michigan highway)|M-24]] near [[Pontiac, Michigan|Pontiac]] to the Flint area opened.<ref name=BH-NP1962>{{cite news |title= New Section of I-75 Opens |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1962-10-26/page-19?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?pep=interstate-75&page=4&psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1962&pey=1963 |location= Benton Harbor, MI |work= The News-Palladium |agency= Associated Press |date= October 26, 1962 |at= Section&nbsp;2, p.&nbsp;19 |oclc= 10117334 |accessdate= March 23, 2013}}</ref> The same year, the freeway gap was filled in between Gaylord and Indian River.<ref>{{cite news |first= Michael |last= Jones |date= February 19, 2008 |title= Five Nuggets of Knowledge about I-75 |url= http://articles.petoskeynews.com/2008-02-19/state-road_24054329 |work= [[Gaylord Herald Times]] |accessdate= August 15, 2013 }}</ref> The [[Sault Ste. Marie International Bridge|International Bridge]] and its approaches opened in Sault Ste. Marie on October 31, 1962.<ref name=IBF/> The following year, a set of segments opened in the Detroit area. The freeway was extended south from Pontiac to 11&nbsp;Mile Road with a connection along [[M-150 (Michigan highway)|M-150]] to [[M-102 (Michigan highway)|M-102]] (8&nbsp;Mile Road). Another section opened to connect with US&nbsp;24 (Telegraph Road) in the [[Woodhaven, Michigan|Woodhaven]] area; a TO I-75 designation was added to connect along US&nbsp;24 and M-102 to M-150.<ref name="MSHD63">{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1963 |section= B11<U+2013>D11, K12<U+2013>L13 }}</ref><ref name=MSHD64>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1964 |section= B11<U+2013>D11, L13 }}</ref> On the other end of the state, the gaps in the freeway across the UP were completed in 1963 as well,<ref name=TCRE1963>{{cite news |title= Completes Hike |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1963-10-31/page-6?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1962&pey=1963&pep=interstate-75&pse=10 |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency=  United Press International |date= October 31, 1963 |page= 6 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 30098364}}</ref> and the section of freeway in Northern Michigan was named the most scenic new highway in the US in 1963 by ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' magazine.<ref name=white1963>{{cite news |last= White |first= Elmer E. |date= November 1, 1963 |title= Michigan Mirror: Nation's Nicest |work= Ludington Daily News |page= 4 |oclc= 27033604 |url=  http://newspaperarchive.com/ludington-daily-news/1963-11-01/page-4?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?pep=interstate-75&page=9&psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1962&pey=1963 |accessdate= March 23, 2013}}</ref><ref name=mackie>{{cite news |last= Mackie |first= John C. |authorlink= John C. Mackie |date= December 26, 1963 |title= John Mackie Lists Many Achievements for 1963 |work= [[Holland Evening Sentinel]] |agency= United Press International |page= 22 |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/holland-evening-sentinel/1963-12-26/page-22?tag=michigan+interstate+75+open+dedicate&rtserp=tags/michigan?pep=interstate-75&plo=open-dedicate&pr=30&psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1961&pey=1969 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 13440201}}</ref> The first part of the Chrysler Freeway opened to traffic on June 26, 1964,<ref name=barnett233/> the southern mile (1.6&nbsp;km) of which was designated [[Interstate 375 (Michigan)|I-375]].<ref name=MSHD65>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1965 |section= M13 }}</ref>

[[File:Interstate Highway plan June 27, 1958 (MI).jpg|thumb|left|1958 numbering plan for Michigan's Interstates|alt=Map of]]
The segment of I-75 through the [[Downriver]] suburbs of Detroit between the US&nbsp;24 (Telegraph Road) connector and [[M-39 (Michigan highway)|M-39]] (Southfield Highway) was completed on December 28, 1966.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1966-12-28/page-15?tag=michigan+freeway&rtserp=tags/michigan-freeway?page=2&psi=52&pci=7&py=1966 |title= Open Section of Freeway |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency= United Press International |date= December 28, 1966 |page= 15 |oclc= 30098364 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> The same year, I-75 was scheduled to open southward from 11&nbsp;Mile Road to M-102 (8&nbsp;Mile Road).<ref>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1966-09-08/page-21?tag=michigan+freeway&rtserp=tags/michigan-freeway?py=1966&psi=52&pci=7 |title= 275-Mile Highway Spans State: New Buffalo to Port Huron; Other Projects |work= The News-Palladium |location= Benton Harbor, MI |page= 21 |date= September 8, 1966 |agency= Associated Press |oclc= 10117334}}</ref> In 1967, two segments of freeway opened. One was from Kawkawlin to [[Standish, Michigan|Standish]] in October,<ref>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/daily-globe/1968-10-29/page-18?tag=michigan+freeway&rtserp=tags/michigan-freeway?py=1968&psi=52&pci=7 |title= New Freeway Stretch To Be Opened Friday |work= Ironwood Daily Globe |agency= Associated Press |date= October 29, 1968 |page= 10 |oclc= 10890811 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> and the other through Detroit extended I-75 along the Fisher Freeway in December.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1967-12-13/page-33?tag=fisher+freeway+detroit&rtserp=tags/fisher-freeway-detroit?ndt=by&py=1960&pey=1969&psi=52&pci=7 |title= Part of Fisher Freeway Opens |work= The News-Palladium |location= Benton Harbor, MI |agency= Associated Press |page= 34 |date= December13, 1967 |oclc= 10117334 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> The first section of M-76 freeway from Standish northwesterly to [[Alger, Michigan|Alger]] was scheduled to open in July 1968.<ref>{{cite news |title= New Freeway Section To Open on July 2 |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/daily-globe/1968-06-19/page-14?tag=michigan+freeway&rtserp=tags/michigan-freeway?page=2&psi=52&pci=7&py=1968 |work= Ironwood Daily Globe |agency= Associated Press |page= 14 |date= June 19, 1968 |oclc= 10890811 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> A {{convert/spell|1|mi|km|adj=on}} section of the Chrysler Freeway through Detroit opened on December 19, 1968, and the remainder was scheduled to open on January 10, 1969.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/daily-globe/1968-12-19/page-20?tag=michigan+freeway&rtserp=tags/michigan-freeway?page=2&psi=52&pci=7&py=1968 |title= Costly Freeway Piece To Open Jan. 10 |date= December 19, 1968 |page= 13 |work=Ironwood Daily Globe |agency= Associated Press |oclc= 10890811 |accessdate= August 15, 2013}}</ref> 

In 1970, I-75 through Detroit was completed, and two additional sections of M-76 were converted to freeway. The northern section ran from the US&nbsp;27-to-I-75 transition south of Grayling to the [[Crawford County, Michigan|Crawford]]<U+2013>[[Roscommon County, Michigan|Roscommon]] county line, and the second was an extension from Alger to the [[West Branch, Michigan|West Branch]] area.<ref name=MDSH70>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of State Highways |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1970 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi |section= G11, H12<U+2013>I12, M13 }}</ref><ref name=MDSH71>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of State Highways |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1971 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi |section= G11, H12<U+2013>I12, M13}}</ref> The first ice-detection system in the state was installed on the River Rouge bridges in the Detroit area in an attempt to maximize driver safety.
<ref name=LDN1970>{{cite news |last= White |first= Elmer E. |date= December 15, 1970 |url= http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HZBaAAAAIBAJ&sjid=GUoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5505,4228476&dq=michigan+interstate-75&hl=en |title= Michigan Mirror: Detection System Started |work= Ludington Daily News |page= 4 |oclc= 27033604 |accessdate= March 23, 2013}}</ref> The next year, the last section of the Chrysler Freeway in [[Hazel Park, Michigan|Hazel Park]] was finished when an interchange for the then-unbuilt [[Interstate 696|I-696]] was completed.<ref name=NP1971-12-06>{{cite news |title= I-75 Complete Inside Michigan |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/benton-harbor-news-palladium/1971-12-06/page-22?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=by&py=1970&pey=1971&pep=interstate-75&pse= |work= The News-Palladium |location= Benton Harbor, MI |agency= Associated Press |page= 33 |date= December 6, 1971 |oclc= 10117334 |accessdate= March 23, 2013}}</ref> Another segment of the M-76 freeway was completed at the same time, bypassing [[Roscommon, Michigan|Roscommon]].<ref name=MDSH71/><ref name=MDSH72>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of State Highways |title= Official Highway Map |year= 1972 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi |section= H12, M13 }}</ref> The final section between Alger and Roscommon was opened on November 1, 1973, in a dedication by Governor [[William G. Milliken]].<ref name=TCRE1973-11-02>{{cite news |url= http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1973-11-02/page-3?tag=interstate+75&rtserp=tags/?psi=52&pci=7&ndt=bd&pd=31&pe=30&pem=11&py=1973&pm=10&pey=1973&pep=interstate-75&pse= |title= Around the State: West Branch |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency= United Press International |date= November 2, 1973 |page= 3 |accessdate= March 23, 2013 |oclc= 30098364}}</ref>

Since the freeway was completed, a few changes have been made to I-75 in Michigan. MDOT truncated US&nbsp;2 to end in St. Ignace by removing it from the I<U+2011>75 freeway in 1983.<ref name="MDOT83">{{cite map |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |title=Official Transportation Map |year=1983 |scale=1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi./1&nbsp;in:23&nbsp;km |section= C10<U+2013>C11}}</ref><ref name="MDOT84">{{cite map |publisher=Michigan Department of Transportation |title=Official Transportation Map |year=1984 |scale=1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi./1&nbsp;in:23&nbsp;km |section=C10<U+2013>C11}}</ref> In 1986, US&nbsp;10 was truncated to Bay City, removing its concurrency with I-75 from there to [[Clarkston, Michigan|Clarkston]].<ref name=MDOT86>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |title= Official Transportation Map |year= 1986 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi&nbsp;/ 1&nbsp;in:23&nbsp;km |section= J12<U+2013>L13 }}</ref><ref name=MDOT87>{{cite map |publisher= Michigan Department of Transportation |title= Official Transportation Map |year= 1987 |scale= 1&nbsp;in:14.5&nbsp;mi&nbsp;/ 1&nbsp;in:23&nbsp;km |section= J12<U+2013>L13 }}</ref> Two years later, the original bascule Zilwaukee Bridge across the Saginaw River was replaced by a much higher structure slightly north of the former bridge.<ref name=blade88/>

===Gateway Project===
{{main|Gateway Project (Detroit)|l1=Gateway Project}}
[[File:Ambassador Gateway Project I-75.jpg|thumb|right|Construction in 2007 during the Gateway Project|alt=Photograph of the Ambassador Bridge and]]
Beginning on February 25, 2008, I-75 closed completely to traffic in both directions from Rosa Parks Boulevard (exit&nbsp;49) to Clark Street (exit&nbsp;47) in Detroit. This facilitated the complete rebuilding of the road as part of the Ambassador Gateway Project to better connect I-75 and I-96 to the [[Ambassador Bridge]]. Through traffic on I-75 was rerouted along [[Interstate 94 in Michigan|I-94]] to [[Interstate 275 (Michigan)|I-275]] and local detours were posted.<ref>{{cite news |first1= Tom |last1= Greenwood |first2= Mike |last2= Wilkinson |lastauthoramp= yes |title= Motorists Maneuver Through Gateway Project Maze |url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DTNB&s_site=detnews&f_site=detnews&f_sitename=Detroit+News%2C+The+%28MI%29&p_multi=DTNB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=11F1AC38364084F0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work= The Detroit News |date= February 26, 2008 |pages=1B, 5B |issn= 1055-2715 |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref> The freeway reopened to traffic in June 2009, five months ahead of schedule.<ref>{{cite news |first= Tom |last= Greenwood |date= June 27, 2009 |title= I-75 To Open for Traffic Next Week at Gateway Project |url= http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=DTNB&s_site=detnews&f_site=detnews&f_sitename=Detroit+News%2C+The+%28MI%29&p_multi=DTNB&p_theme=gannett&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=129B6AF812080EF0&p_field_direct-0=document_id&p_perpage=10&p_sort=YMD_date:D&s_trackval=GooglePM |work= The Detroit News |page= 3A |issn= 1055-2715 |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref> The overall project to realign and connect the bridge to the freeways was mired in lawsuits between MDOT and the private company that owns the bridge. The [[Manuel Moroun|company's owner]] was jailed for [[contempt of court]] during court proceedings in early 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first1= Matt |last1= Helms |first2= John |last2= Gallagher |lastauthoramp= yes |date= January 12, 2012 |title= Mich. Billionaire, 84, Jailed over Bridge Dispute |url= http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/nation/story/2012-01-12/michigan-canada-ambassador-bridge/52517112/1 |work= [[USA Today]] |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref> MDOT was later ordered to assume responsibility for construction,<ref>{{cite news |first=  Jeff T. |last= Wattrick |date= March 16, 2012 |title= MDOT Launches 'Getting Gateway to the Finish Line' Social Campaign |url= http://www.mlive.com/news/detroit/index.ssf/2012/03/mdot_launches_getting_gateway.html |work= MLive |location= Detroit |publisher= Booth Newspapers |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref> and the department completed the project on September 21, 2012.<ref>{{cite news |first= David |last= Muller |date= September 20, 2012 |title= Detroit Neighborhoods To See Less Truck Traffic as $230 million Gateway Plaza Opens |url= http://www.mlive.com/business/detroit/index.ssf/2012/09/detroit_neighborhoods_to_see_l.html |work= MLive |location= Detroit |publisher= Booth Newspapers |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref>
{{-}}

==Freeway names==
{{multiple image
|align= left
|direction= horizontal
|image1= Walter P. Chrysler at White House (cropped).png
|width1= 165
|alt1= Portrait of Walter P. Chrysler
|image2= Prentiss Marsh Brown.jpg
|width2=136
|alt2= Portrait of Prentiss M. Brown
|footer= Segments of I-75 in Michigan are named for Walter P. Chrysler (left) and Prentiss M. Brown (right) among others. 
}}
I-75 has five named segments in Michigan. The southernmost section from the state line north to the Detroit area is the Detroit<U+2013>Toledo Expressway.<ref name=WCRCreport>{{cite report |author= Board of Wayne County Road Commissioners |authorlink=Wayne County Road Commission |year= 1960 |title= Route Location Study: FAI&nbsp;75: Detroit<U+2013>Toledo Expressway to Rouge River |publisher= Michigan State Highway Department |oclc= 23314996}}</ref> The segment through southern and central Detroit is known as the Fisher Freeway. It was dedicated on September 17, 1970, to the Fisher Brothers, who founded [[Fisher Body]], later a part of [[General Motors]].<ref name=barnett81-2>[[#Barnett|Barnett]], pp.&nbsp;81<U+2013>2.</ref> After the curve in downtown Detroit, I-75 follows the Walter P. Chrysler Freeway northward. That segment is named for [[Walter P. Chrysler]], founder of [[Chrysler]]. The name was chosen by the Detroit Common Council on November 6, 1957, and codified in state law in 1990; the state definition for the name places the northern end of the designation at the Oakland<U+2013>Genesee county line.<ref name=barnett233>[[#Barnett|Barnett]], p.&nbsp;233.</ref>

Officially, the entire length of I-75 in Michigan is the American Legion Memorial Highway. As a practical matter, this name is not used on the southernmost segments of the Interstate. The [[American Legion]] was honored with the designation in 1969 in a state law that required private interests to finance the signage. Public Act&nbsp;174 of 1984 redesignated I-75 in honor of the group and placed responsibility for signage in MDOT's hands.<ref name=barnett22-3>[[#Barnett|Barnett]], pp.&nbsp;22<U+2013>3.</ref> Another name that was applied to all of I-75 was the Michigan Bicentennial Freedom Way. Designated by Senate Concurrent Resolution&nbsp;216 of 1975, the name only applied to the freeway in 1976.<ref>{{cite web |first= J. |last= Hunault |date= January 8, 2002 |title= Public Act 142 of 2001: Second Analysis |url= http://www.legislature.mi.gov/documents/2001-2002/billanalysis/House/htm/2001-HLA-4878-B.htm |location= Lansing |publisher= House Fiscal Agency |accessdate= August 18, 2013}}</ref> The designation was formally repealed in 2001.<ref>{{cite web |author= [[Michigan Legislature]] |date= October 26, 2001 |title= Memorial Highways Act (Public Act 142 of 2001) |url= http://www.legislature.mi.gov/(S(t5evgs55wwcpy52x4vc1jt3k))/mileg.aspx?page=getObject&objectName=mcl-250-1100|work= [[Michigan Compiled Laws]] |at= Section 250.1100 |accessdate= August 18, 2013}}</ref>

Two other segments near the Straits of Mackinac were named in 1976 for figures instrumental in the construction of the Mackinac Bridge. From the Cheboygan<U+2013>Otsego county line north to the bridge, I-75 was named for [[G. Mennen Williams]], the former governor once called "Michigan's Politician of the Century" in the press.<ref name=barnett88>[[#Barnett|Barnett]], p.&nbsp;88.</ref> The section in Mackinac County from the northern end of the Mackinac Bridge was named for [[Prentiss M. Brown]], the former [[U.S. House of Representatives|Congressman]] and [[U.S. Senate|Senator]] who served on the [[Mackinac Bridge Authority|MBA]] board until his death in 1971.<ref name=barnett177-8>[[#Barnett|Barnett]], pp.&nbsp;178<U+2013>8.</ref>

==Monumental bridges==
{{main|Sault Ste. Marie International Bridge|Mackinac Bridge|Zilwaukee Bridge|l1=International Bridge}}
[[File:Zilwaukee-Bridge-September-.jpg|thumb|right|Zilwaukee Bridge|alt=Photograph looking north at the]]
Along its route in the state, I-75 utilizes three of Michigan's monumental bridges. The first of them is the Zilwaukee Bridge near Saginaw. The original bridge across the Saginaw River at Zilwaukee was built in 1960 as a [[bascule bridge]] to allow shipping traffic to use the river. Opening the drawbridge would back traffic up on I-75/US&nbsp;10/US&nbsp;23 for upwards of four hours on holiday weekends.<ref name=hyde166>[[#Hyde|Hyde]], p.&nbsp;166.</ref> Approved in 1974, construction on the replacement bridge started in October 1979. A major construction accident in August 1982 delayed completion of the new Zilwaukee Bridge; a bridge pier partially collapsed when contractors overloaded a section under construction. The affected {{convert|300|ft|m|adj=on}} deck segment tilted to rest {{convert/spell|3|ft|m}} higher on one end and {{convert/spell|5|ft|m}} lower on the other.<ref name=hyde168>[[#Hyde|Hyde]], p.&nbsp;168.</ref> The structure was originally supposed to cost $76.8&nbsp;million with a 1983 completion date; in the end it cost $131.3&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-NGDPPC|131300000|1983|r=-4}}}} in 2010{{Inflation-fn|US-NGDPPC}}) when the southbound span finally opened on September 19, 1988.<ref name=blade88>{{cite news |author=Staff Writer |date=September 19, 1988 |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=C3BRAAAAIBAJ&sjid=zw0EAAAAIBAJ&pg=3349,13274&dq=zilwaukee+bridge&hl=en |title=Zilwaukee Bridge Now Open North, South<U+2014>Partly |work= The Blade |location= Toledo, OH |page=1 |oclc= 12962717 |accessdate= October 29, 2012}}</ref> The structure is the largest concrete segmental bridge in the United States.<ref>{{cite news |title= A Brief History of Paving |work= The Grand Rapids Press| page= A8 |oclc= 9975013}}</ref>

[[File:Mackinac Bridge from the air4.jpg|thumb|left|Mackinac Bridge|alt=Aerial photograph of the]]
The second is the Mackinac Bridge that connects Michigan's two peninsulas at the Straits of Mackinac. A structure was first proposed in 1888 by one of the directors of the [[Grand Hotel (Mackinac Island)|Grand Hotel]] on [[Mackinac Island]]. Car ferry service was started in 1923 to cross the straits, and a bridge authority was first created in 1934 to investigate the possibility of building a permanent connection across the straits. This early authority started with a 1921 proposal for a series of bridges that would have connected [[Cheboygan, Michigan|Cheboygan]] to [[St. Ignace, Michigan|St. Ignace]] by way of [[Bois Blanc Island (Michigan)|Bois Blanc]], [[Round Island (Michigan)|Round]], and Mackinac islands. The federal [[Public Works Administration]] rejected loan and grant requests for that project. A second, direct crossing was then proposed based on designs used for the [[Tacoma Narrows Bridge (1940)|Tacoma Narrows Bridge]]. The collapse of that bridge and World War II delayed any further work on a structure beyond tests of the lake bottom and the construction of the {{convert|4200|ft|m|adj=mid|-long}} causeway on the St. Ignace side; the first bridge authority was abolished in 1947.<ref name=hyde159>[[#Hyde|Hyde]], pp.&nbsp;159<U+2013>66.</ref> The current agency was created on June 6, 1950.<ref name=Rubin13>[[#Rubin|Rubin]], pp.&nbsp;13<U+2013>7.</ref>

The MBA was authorized in 1952 to sell bonds to finance construction,<ref name=hyde159/> which were sold on December 17, 1953, to finance the $99.8&nbsp;million (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-NGDPPC|99800000|1953|r=-5}}}} in 2010{{Inflation-fn|US-NGDPPC}}) cost of the bridge.<ref name=rubin103>[[#Rubin|Rubin]], pp.&nbsp;103<U+2013>7.</ref> The structure was designed by [[David B. Steinman]] and built by [[Merritt-Chapman & Scott]] for the substructure and the [[American Bridge Company]] division of [[U.S. Steel Corporation]] for the superstructure. Construction started in 1954 and the Mackinac Bridge opened to traffic on November 1, 1957. Final work on the bridge was completed in September 1958. Overall, the structure has a {{convert|3800|ft|m|adj=on}} central suspension span flanked by two {{convert|1800|ft|m|adj=on}} side spans. With the two backstay spans, the Mackinac Bridge is {{convert|8614|ft|m}} long between cable anchorages, the longest in the world at the time it opened.{{#tag:ref|The [[Akashi Kaiky<U+014D> Bridge|Akashi Kaiky<U+014D>]] and [[Great Belt Bridge|Great Belt]] bridges in the [[Eastern Hemisphere]] are each longer between anchorages at {{convert|12826|ft|m}} and {{convert|8,921|ft|m}} respectively,<ref>{{cite news |title= Bridge Facts |work= [[Monroe Evening News|The Monroe Evening News]] |date= September 2, 2007 |page= 1E |oclc= 35981181}}</ref> but the Mackinac is still the longest between anchorages in the [[Western Hemisphere]],<ref>{{cite news |first= Susan R. |last= Pollack |date= May 23, 2007 |title= The Mighty Mac Is Turning 50!: Head North This Summer for Big Doings around Mackinaw and the Upper Peninsula |work= The Detroit News |page= 3E |issn= 1055-2715 }}</ref> and crosses a wider body of water.|group=lower-alpha}} The total length of the structure is {{convert|26444|ft|m}} with two {{Convert|555|ft|m|adj=mid|-tall}} towers and {{convert|155|ft|m}} of clearance for passing ships under the main span.<ref name=hyde159/> In 2000, the bridge was named "Michigan's No. 1 Civil Engineering Project of the 20th Century" in 2000 by the Michigan Section of the [[American Society of Civil Engineers]] (ASCE), and the structure was named a [[National Historic Civil Engineering Landmark]] in 2010 by the national ASCE.<ref>{{cite news |first= Doris |last= Parker|title= Celebrating the Soo Locks, Mackinac Bridge |work= [[Cheboygan Daily Tribune]] |agency= Associated Press |date= June 23, 2012 |page= A2 |issn= 0746-665X}}</ref>

[[File:Soo Locks International Bridge 2010-04 USACE.jpg|thumb|right|Part of the International Bridge|alt=Photograph of]]
The northernmost of the three monumental bridges along I-75 is the International Bridge, linking the twin cities of Sault Ste. Marie in [[Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan|Michigan]] and [[Sault Ste. Marie, Ontario|Ontario]]. The governments on each side of the international border formed a bridge authority to build a highway bridge in 1935.<ref name=hyde159>[[#Hyde|Hyde]], p.&nbsp;159.</ref> Construction started on the structure September 16, 1960.<ref name=IBF>{{cite news |url=http://newspaperarchive.com/traverse-city-record-eagle/1962-10-31?tag=sault+ste+marie+international+bridge&rtserp=tags/sault-ste-marie-international-bridge?pr=30&psb=date&page=2&py=1962 |title= New International Bridge Opened Today |work= Traverse City Record-Eagle |agency= United Press International |date= October&nbsp;31, 1962 |oclc= 30098364 |page= 1 |accessdate= August&nbsp;15, 2013}}</ref> The International Bridge is nearly {{convert/spell|3|mi|km}} long, encompassing spans over the American and Canadian navigation channels for the [[Soo Locks]] and the [[St. Marys River (Michigan<U+2013>Ontario)|St. Mary's River]]. The American approach is {{convert|2471|ft|m}}, and the Canadian approach is {{convert|2942|ft|m}}. The center span over the river is {{convert|9280|ft|m}}, flanked by {{convert|1260|ft|m|adj=on}} and {{convert|830|ft|m|adj=on}} spans over the American and Canadian shipping channels, respectively. The bridge was designed by the same firm that handled the Mackinac Bridge for a cost of $20&nbsp;million<ref name=hyde159/> (equivalent to ${{Formatprice|{{Inflation|US-NGDPPC|20000000|1962|r=-6}}}} in 2010{{Inflation-fn|US-NGDPPC}}). It opened to traffic on October 31, 1962.<ref name=IBF/>
{{-}}

