==Related trunklines==
[[File:US Route 2 Western Segment Eastern Terminus.JPG|thumb|right|Southern end of the business loop for St. Ignace|alt=Photograph of]]
There are four [[List of auxiliary Interstate Highways|auxiliary Interstate Highways]] for I-75 in Michigan. [[Interstate 275 (Michigan)|I-275]] begins as a loop from northern Monroe County and continues to connect with I-96 and I-696. The freeway serves the population of western Wayne County and [[Detroit Metropolitan Wayne County Airport]].<ref name=MDOT12/> The highway was originally intended to connect with I-75 north of Pontiac.<ref name="YBD">{{cite map |url=http://www.ajfroggie.com/roads/yellowbook/detroit.jpg |title= General Location of National System of Interstate Highways Including All Additional Routes at Urban Areas Designated in September 1955 (Yellow Book) |inset= Detroit, Michigan |publisher= Bureau of Public Roads |year= 1955 |accessdate= October&nbsp;27, 2012}}</ref> [[Interstate 375 (Michigan)|I-375]] was the shortest signed Interstate in the nation;{{#tag:ref|I-375 was the shortest signed Interstate Highway until [[Interstate 110 (Texas)|I-110]] was signed in 2010;<ref name=RMN08/><ref name=I-110sign>{{cite sign |author= Staff |year= 2010 |url= http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Interstate-110-El-Paso.jpg |title= Northbound I-110/US&nbsp;54/I-10/US&nbsp;180 Pull-Through Sign |medium= Highway guide sign |location= El Paso, TX |publisher= [[Texas Department of Transportation]] |accessdate= October&nbsp;27, 2012}}</ref> [[Interstate 878 (New York)|I-878]] and [[Interstate 315|I-315]] in [[New York City]] and [[Great Falls, Montana]], are shorter,<ref name=RLFL2>{{cite web |author= Staff |url= http://www.fhwa.dot.gov/reports/routefinder/table2.htm |title= Table&nbsp;2: Auxiliary Routes of the Dwight D. Eisenhower National System Of Interstate and Defense Highways as of October 31, 2002 |work= Route Log and Finder List |publisher= Federal Highway Administration |date= October 31, 2002 |accessdate= March 25, 2010}}</ref> but unsigned.<ref name=RMN08>{{cite map |publisher= Rand McNally |year= 2009 |title= The Road Atlas |at= Section N16, Great Falls inset, p.&nbsp;61; Section J13<U+2013>14, New York City & Vicinity inset, p.&nbsp;73; Section WT3, El Paso inset, p.&nbsp;99 |isbn= 0-528-93981-5}}</ref>|group=lower-alpha}}  It serves the immediate downtown [[Detroit]] area.<ref name=MDOT12/> [[Interstate 475 (Michigan)|I-475]] is known as the UAW Freeway and the David Dunbar Buick Freeway.<ref name="Barnett40">[[#Barnett|Barnett]], pp.&nbsp;40<U+2013>1, 215.</ref> This freeway serves Flint's downtown areas as I-75 goes to the west side of the city.<ref name=MDOT12/> The fourth auxiliary Interstate is [[Interstate 675 (Michigan)|I-675]], a loop into the city of Saginaw<ref name=MDOT12/> that served as an alternate to I-75 when the drawbridge over the Saginaw River was still operating.<ref name=hyde166/>

In addition to the auxiliary Interstates, there are eight current [[Business routes of Interstate 75 in Michigan|business routes]] related to the freeway in the state. These business loops and spurs provide signed connections into the downtowns of [[Interstate 75 Business (Pontiac, Michigan)|Pontiac]], [[Interstate 75 Business (Bay City, Michigan)|Bay City]], [[Interstate 75 Business (West Branch, Michigan)|West Branch]], [[Interstate 75 Business (Roscommon, Michigan)|Roscommon]], [[Interstate 75 Business (Grayling, Michigan)|Grayling]], [[Interstate 75 Business (Gaylord, Michigan)|Gaylord]], [[Interstate 75 Business (St. Ignace, Michigan)|St. Ignace]], and [[Interstate 75 Business (Sault Ste. Marie, Michigan)|Sault Ste. Marie]].<ref name=MDOT12/> A ninth highway was previously designated in [[Interstate 75 Business (Saginaw, Michigan)|Saginaw]] as well.<ref name=MDSH71/>

